{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17533171","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17533171"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T16:33:19+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T16:33:19+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14761"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"14761","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/14761"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.78,0.07,0.12,0.01,0.01]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7452"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"106669"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"7452","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/7452"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14761"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"89148"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"14"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"34"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"306"},{"type":"tags","id":"3657"},{"type":"tags","id":"4931"},{"type":"tags","id":"4947"},{"type":"tags","id":"6523"},{"type":"tags","id":"9222"},{"type":"tags","id":"9315"},{"type":"tags","id":"12913"},{"type":"tags","id":"12920"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"18231"},{"type":"contributions","id":"39709"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"106669","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/106669"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 45-year-old man presents to the General Practice clinic with a three-month history of right lower leg pain and intermittent discharge from a small opening in his skin. He sustained an open fracture of his tibia in a motorcycle accident eight months ago, which was surgically fixed with internal hardware. He has no other significant medical history and takes no regular medications.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears well with vital signs within normal limits. There is a small sinus tract with purulent discharge over the anterior aspect of his right tibia. The surrounding skin is erythematous and tender to touch. Plain radiographs reveal a segment of dense bone separated from surrounding bone by a radiolucent line, surrounded by thick, irregular new bone formation.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely causative pathogen in this case?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Staphylococcus aureus","Pseudomonas aeruginosa","Streptococcus pyogenes","Escherichia coli","Enterococcus faecalis"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with chronic osteomyelitis following an open fracture and internal fixation. \u003Cstrong\u003EStaphylococcus aureus\u003C/strong\u003E is the most common causative organism in post-traumatic osteomyelitis, accounting for approximately 50-70% of cases. It has several virulence factors that allow it to adhere to bone and prosthetic materials, and form biofilms that make treatment challenging.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPseudomonas aeruginosa\u003C/strong\u003E can cause osteomyelitis, particularly in cases involving puncture wounds to the foot or in intravenous drug users. While it can be isolated in post-traumatic cases, it is less common than S. aureus.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EStreptococcus pyogenes\u003C/strong\u003E is a less common cause of osteomyelitis than \u003Cem\u003ES. aureus\u003C/em\u003E. While it can cause bone infections, it is not typically associated with post-traumatic osteomyelitis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EEscherichia coli\u003C/strong\u003E and other gram-negative organisms are more commonly associated with vertebral osteomyelitis or infections following urological procedures. They are less frequently isolated in post-traumatic osteomyelitis of long bones.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EEnterococcus faecalis\u003C/strong\u003E is an uncommon cause of osteomyelitis but may be seen in diabetic foot infections or in polymicrobial infections. It is rarely the sole pathogen in post-traumatic osteomyelitis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe presence of internal hardware increases the risk of infection as it provides a surface for bacterial adherence and biofilm formation. Treatment typically requires both prolonged antibiotics and surgical debridement, often with removal of infected hardware.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Staphylococcus aureus is the most common causative organism in post-traumatic osteomyelitis.","Risk factors for post-traumatic osteomyelitis include open fractures and internal fixation devices.","Chronic osteomyelitis typically presents with persistent pain, intermittent discharge, and sinus tract formation."],"references":["Masters EA, Trombetta RP, de Mesy Bentley KL, et al. Evolving concepts in bone infection: redefining \u0022biofilm\u0022, \u0022acute vs. chronic osteomyelitis\u0022, \u0022the immune proteome\u0022 and \u0022local antibiotic therapy\u0022. Bone Res. 2019;7:20. Published 2019 Jul 15. doi:10.1038/s41413-019-0061-z Available from: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/35169289/","Hofstee MI, Muthukrishnan G, Atkins GJ, et al. Current Concepts of Osteomyelitis: From Pathologic Mechanisms to Advanced Research Methods. Am J Pathol. 2020;190(6):1151-1163. doi:10.1016/j.ajpath.2020.02.007 Available from: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/32194053/","Masters EA, Ricciardi BF, Bentley KLM, Moriarty TF, Schwarz EM, Muthukrishnan G. Skeletal infections: microbial pathogenesis, immunity and clinical management. Nat Rev Microbiol. 2022;20(7):385-400. doi:10.1038/s41579-022-00686-0 Available from: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/31646012/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"89148"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14761"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"89148","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/89148"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-06-21T16:16:36+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-07-02T00:08:16+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7452"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"106669"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"14","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/14"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udda0","name":"Infectious Diseases","synonyms":["ID"],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2021-05-21T07:51:58+09:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"25","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/25"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc68\u200d\ud83d\udc69\u200d\ud83d\udc66","name":"General Practice","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"6"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"34","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/34"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\uddb4","name":"Orthopaedics","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:47:20+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"2"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"64","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/64"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Diagnosis","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"create